WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:01.896
Claude Shannon figured out how the 

00:00:01.896 --> 00:00:04.443
compressibility of English text depends on how 

00:00:04.443 --> 00:00:07.043
predictable it is, so he made multiple attempts 

00:00:07.043 --> 00:00:09.482
at understanding the probability of each new 

00:00:09.482 --> 00:00:10.620
character in English.

00:00:10.940 --> 00:00:13.061
His earliest experiments involved looking at 

00:00:13.061 --> 00:00:15.089
specific short sequences of characters and 

00:00:15.089 --> 00:00:17.400
tracking the statistics of what tended to follow.

00:00:17.660 --> 00:00:19.343
For example, you could scan through a 

00:00:19.343 --> 00:00:20.982
couple books, look at every instance 

00:00:20.982 --> 00:00:22.709
where you see the letters TH and build 

00:00:22.709 --> 00:00:24.880
up a table of what tends to follow and how often.

00:00:25.060 --> 00:00:27.013
The problem here is that this completely 

00:00:27.013 --> 00:00:29.300
breaks down for longer sequences of characters, 

00:00:29.300 --> 00:00:31.110
most notably those that never show up 

00:00:31.110 --> 00:00:32.540
in the text you're looking at.

00:00:32.640 --> 00:00:35.197
But longer sequences give more context to guide 

00:00:35.197 --> 00:00:37.808
a prediction, which means that's when text is at 

00:00:37.808 --> 00:00:40.420
its most predictable and hence most compressible.

00:00:40.620 --> 00:00:42.739
So to really understand the compressibility 

00:00:42.739 --> 00:00:44.570
of language, he needed some other way 

00:00:44.570 --> 00:00:46.160
to ask about these probabilities.

00:00:46.540 --> 00:00:48.682
So he turned to one of the most readily 

00:00:48.682 --> 00:00:50.771
available models of language available 

00:00:50.771 --> 00:00:52.700
to him in the 1940s: His wife, Betty.

00:00:53.040 --> 00:00:54.470
As the story goes, he pulled out 

00:00:54.470 --> 00:00:55.856
a book and asked her to predict 

00:00:55.856 --> 00:00:57.460
each new letter from a given passage.

00:00:57.460 --> 00:00:59.138
Every time she guessed incorrectly, 

00:00:59.138 --> 00:01:00.723
he wrote down the correct letter, 

00:01:00.723 --> 00:01:02.495
and every time she guessed correctly, 

00:01:02.495 --> 00:01:04.360
he would replace the letter with a dash.

00:01:04.620 --> 00:01:06.939
His idea was that this new string of text 

00:01:06.939 --> 00:01:09.204
had fewer actual letters, but it carried 

00:01:09.204 --> 00:01:11.578
the same information, in the sense that it 

00:01:11.578 --> 00:01:13.953
should give just the right prompting for a 

00:01:13.953 --> 00:01:16.660
duplicate of his wife to fill in the entire text.

00:01:16.860 --> 00:01:19.014
This was a start, but his formal definition 

00:01:19.014 --> 00:01:20.777
of information requires knowing the 

00:01:20.777 --> 00:01:23.030
actual probabilities assigned to new letters, 

00:01:23.030 --> 00:01:24.500
so he needed something better.

00:01:24.500 --> 00:01:26.598
In his 1950 paper, Prediction and Entropy 

00:01:26.598 --> 00:01:28.597
of Printed English, Shannon outlined an 

00:01:28.597 --> 00:01:30.695
experiment interviewing more people where 

00:01:30.695 --> 00:01:32.894
instead of just logging whether their guess 

00:01:32.894 --> 00:01:34.993
was correct or wrong, he would record how 

00:01:34.993 --> 00:01:37.091
many guesses were necessary for his human 

00:01:37.091 --> 00:01:39.540
guessers to come up with the correct next letter.

00:01:39.840 --> 00:01:42.127
Separately, he combined the idea of statistics 

00:01:42.127 --> 00:01:44.269
with short sequences with number of guesses 

00:01:44.269 --> 00:01:46.702
to make an estimate at the implicit probabilities 

00:01:46.702 --> 00:01:48.844
that people were assigning to the true next 

00:01:48.844 --> 00:01:50.840
letter, based on their number of guesses.

00:01:50.840 --> 00:01:52.870
His final estimate was that given at 

00:01:52.870 --> 00:01:54.681
least 100 characters of context, 

00:01:54.681 --> 00:01:56.821
English should, at least in principle, 

00:01:56.821 --> 00:01:59.071
be compressible down to around 1 bit per 

00:01:59.071 --> 00:01:59.620
character.

00:02:00.000 --> 00:02:02.548
And I want you to notice, in order to make this 

00:02:02.548 --> 00:02:05.043
estimate, he was forced to go beyond pure data 

00:02:05.043 --> 00:02:07.380
analysis and probe at something intelligent.

00:02:07.800 --> 00:02:09.483
Today, more than 75 years later, 

00:02:09.483 --> 00:02:11.830
the way we actually achieve compression close 

00:02:11.830 --> 00:02:14.228
to this limit is not through merely probing at 

00:02:14.228 --> 00:02:16.574
intelligence, but by making our best attempts 

00:02:16.574 --> 00:02:17.340
to engineer it.

00:02:17.340 --> 00:02:19.003
This all comes from the first video 

00:02:19.003 --> 00:02:20.619
in a short series I'm making about 

00:02:20.619 --> 00:02:22.560
the idea that compression is intelligence.

00:02:22.940 --> 00:02:24.180
If you want more, take a look at the channel.

